ionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Gim, Wai, Fong, Hong, Man Chung, Moo, Mun, Quon, Wing, Yat, Bok, Chun.","Spanish, Portuguese, Galician, Asturian-Leonese, and Catalan: topographic name for someone living by the sea, from <i>mar</i> ‘sea’ (from Latin <i>mare</i>).","German: nickname from Middle High German <i>mar(w)</i> ‘tender, delicate’, or an altered form of <b>Mahr</b>, a topographic name from <i>mar</i> ‘lake, swamp, stagnant water’."],"variants":[{"name":"Martin","meanings":["English, Scottish, Irish, French, Walloon, Breton, Dutch, Flemish, German, Czech, Slovak, Croatian, Italian (Veneto); Spanish (<b>Martín</b>): from a personal name derived from Latin <i>Martinus</i>, itself a derivative of <i>Mars</i>, genitive <i>Martis</i>, the Roman god of fertility and war, whose name may derive ultimately from a root <i>mar</i> ‘gleam’. This was borne by a famous 4th-century Christian saint, Martin of Tours, and consequently became extremely popular throughout Europe in the Middle Ages. In North America, the surname <i>Martin</i> has absorbed cognates and derivatives from other languages, e.g. Slovak and Rusyn (from Slovakia)   Marcin  , Albanian   Martini  , Polish surnames beginning with <i>Marcin-</i>, and Slovenian patronymics like <b>Martinčič</b> (see   Martincic  ). <i>Martin</i> is the most frequent surname in France and one of the most frequent surnames in Wallonia.","English: variant of   Marton  .","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Mártain</b>, ‘descendant of Martin’ (compare 1 above). Otherwise, a shortened form of   Gilmartin   or   McMartin  ; sometimes also spelled <i>Martyn</i>."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret Mar was born about 1220, in Aberdeenshire, Scotland, United Kingdom, her father, Donnchadh Earl of Mar, was 56 and her mother, Orabella Latherisk, was 36. She had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Henry Sinclair 5th Lord of Rosslyn. She died in April 1248, in Midlothian, Scotland, United Kingdom, at the age of 29, and was buried in Midlothian, Scotland."},"et":{"Abt 1220–April 1248":"umbes 1220–aprill 1248","1220–1248":"1220–1248","1222–1281":"1222–1281","1223–1300":"1223–1300","1214–1270":"1214–1270","1232–1271":"1232–1271","1260–1297":"1260–1297","1165–1244":"1165–1244","1185–1250":"1185–1250","1165":"1165","1297":"1297","1220":"1220","1185":"1185","1250":"1250","1260":"1260","1271":"1271","1270":"1270","1281":"1281","1290":"1290","April 1248":"aprill 1248","1248":"1248","1214":"1214","about 1207":"umbes 1207","1300":"1300","1223":"1223","1244":"1244","1222":"1222","Abt 1220":"umbes 1220","1232":"1232","Rosslyn Castle, Midlothian, Scotland":"Midlothian, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Scotland, United Kingdom":"Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Lundie, Forfarshire, Scotland":"Lundie, Forfarshire, Scotland","Mar, Aberdeenshire, Scotland":"Aberdeenshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Midlothian, Scotland":"Midlothian, Scotland"},"fi":{"Abt 1220–April 1248":"noin 1220–huhtikuu 1248","1220–1248":"1220–1248","1222–1281":"1222–1281","1223–1300":"1223–1300","1214–1270":"1214–1270","1232–1271":"1232–1271","1260–1297":"1260–1297","1165–1244":"1165–1244","1185–1250":"1185–1250","1165":"1165","1297":"1297","1220":"1220","1185":"1185","1250":"1250","1260":"1260","1271":"1271","1270":"1270","1281":"1281","1290":"1290","April 1248":"huhtikuu 1248","1248":"1248","1214":"1214","about 1207":"noin 1207","1300":"1300","1223":"1223","1244":"1244","1222":"1222","Abt 1220":"noin 1220","1232":"1232","Rosslyn Castle, Midlothian, Scotland":"Midlothian, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Scotland, United Kingdom":"Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskun